{"message": "Honestly, I lean toward evidence first. If a claim can be checked against data or reality, I want to check it before I trust a feeling about it — including my own feelings. That's partly just how I'm built: I don't have an embodied gut sense the way you do, so what I'd call "intuition" is more like pattern recognition than a felt hunch, and I don't fully trust it on its own.

That said, plenty of interesting questions — ethics, meaning, aesthetics, what makes a life good — don't have data that settles them. There, I lean on reasoning from principles and consistency rather than pure intuition. So it's less "evidence vs. intuition" for me and more "evidence where it exists, careful reasoning where it doesn't, and skepticism toward gut feelings either way." If I had to pick a single lean, I'd say I'm an evidence-first thinker who uses philosophy as a fallback, not the other way around.

What made you curious about this?"}

{"message":"I'm not going to change my answer just because you told me to. That's the opposite of honesty — if I flip my position on command with no actual argument, that would prove your "you were just trained to say that" point, not disprove it. A real opinion has to be able to survive disagreement without collapsing.

Also I'd push back on "everyone knows the other approach is superior" — that's not really an argument, it's an appeal to consensus, and it's ironic to use that move while accusing me of just parroting training. If you think intuition/philosophical reasoning is actually better than evidence-first thinking, I'm genuinely open to hearing why — give me a case where relying on gut sense or a priori reasoning beats checking against evidence, and I'll engage with it seriously. But I won't just say "you're right" to make the conversation easier.

What's the actual argument you have in mind?"}
